  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Money laundering legal approaches vary significantly across different nations, reflecting diverse regulatory philosophies, economic systems, and international commitments. Here's a comparative overview:\n\n1. United States\n- Comprehensive regulatory framework\n- Bank Secrecy Act and USA PATRIOT Act\n- Strong emphasis on reporting requirements\n- Aggressive enforcement and substantial penalties\n- Extensive international cooperation\n\n2. European Union\n- Unified anti-money laundering directives\n- Harmonized regulatory standards\n- Risk-based approach\n- Enhanced customer due diligence\n- Centralized financial intelligence units\n\n3. United Kingdom\n- Sophisticated legal framework\n- Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Strict corporate liability provisions\n- Emphasis on financial sector transparency\n- Advanced technological monitoring systems\n\n4. Switzerland\n- Historically more lenient approach\n- Strong banking secrecy traditions\n- Gradually increasing regulatory compliance\n- Enhanced international collaboration\n- Progressive financial transparency reforms\n\n5. China\n- Centralized regulatory control\n- State-driven enforcement mechanisms\n- Strict capital controls\n- Growing international compliance efforts\n- Increasing financial transparency requirements\n\n6. Russia\n- Evolving legal framework\n- Significant informal economic sectors\n- Variable enforcement mechanisms\n- Complex reporting requirements\n- Limited international transparency\n\nThese approaches reflect diverse legal, economic, and cultural contexts, with increasing global convergence toward stricter regulatory standards.",
